Winner: `iterations-3.ts` (86 lines).

Reasoning — compared against the other two on the same behaviour (identical exports, identical stage semantics, identical discount math):

| | iterations-1 (105) | iterations-2 (94) | iterations-3 (86) |
|---|---|---|---|
| stage wiring | array of `[name, fn]` tuples + loop in a free function `runStages` | free function `stage(hooks, name, run)` called 4× | private method `this.stage(name, run)` called 4× |
| discount logic | separate `applyDiscounts` function | separate `applyDiscounts` function | inlined directly in the `"discount"` stage closure |
| indirection | highest — table-driven loop obscures the fixed 4-stage pipeline for no reuse benefit | medium — helper function is fine but still an extra top-level symbol plus a `hooks` param threaded around | lowest — `stage` reads `this.hooks`/`this.vatRate` directly, no threading |

Iteration-1's tuple-array/loop is generalising something that's always exactly 4 fixed stages — indirection without payoff. Iteration-2 fixes that but still splits discount logic into its own top-level function purely to avoid inlining. Iteration-3 collapses both: `stage` is a private method (no parameter threading), and discounts sit inline where they're used. Nothing is lost — same JSDoc, same types, same currency/rounding guard, same hook-firing order.

